<subSubSection box="[199,941,1698,1723]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,258,1902]" box="[199,941,1698,1723]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1699,1723]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name refers to the unusual beauty of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,258,1902]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1734,1759]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Discussion.</emphasis>
As with the Mexican 
<taxonomicName box="[577,749,1735,1759]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="updikei">
<emphasis box="[577,749,1735,1759]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Agrilus updikei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[802,926,1735,1759]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marthae">
<emphasis box="[802,926,1735,1759]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. marthae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the deep transverse depression on the pronotum gives a stronger visual impression of a separate red head. The small post-scutellar spot of silvery setae is unique in these first six larger species. In other respects it is visually similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1078,1253,1807,1831]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="updikei">
<emphasis box="[1078,1253,1807,1831]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Agrilus updikei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has a welldefined prehumeral carina that 
<taxonomicName box="[506,621,1843,1867]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="updikei">
<emphasis box="[506,621,1843,1867]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. updikei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks. This and the following Costa Rican species possess more or less rounded elytral apices rather than the broad and emarginate or transversely truncate ones of the other large species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
